

scene_beat_test_input: str = """{"story_title": "Vacancy at the Starlight", "synopsis": "In rural New Mexico in 1977, freelance radio journalist Elena \"Nell\" Cruz is driving a lonely desert highway when her car breaks down near the long-abandoned Starlight Motel. Drawn in by a phantom voice on her CB radio and the motel's impossible flickering vacancy sign, Elena takes shelter for the night and finds herself trapped inside a place where time stalls, memories repeat, and missing travelers never truly checked out. As she pieces together the motel's history with the help of a frightened former maid, a guilt-ridden county deputy, and the ghost of a teenage hitchhiker, Elena must expose the crimes of the motel's dead manager before dawn or become one more voice lost in the static. The tone is eerie, slow-burning, and atmospheric, blending Southwestern gothic horror, analog ghost-story textures, and 1970s roadside Americana.", "player_character": {"character_data": {"uuid": "9abcfba5-b69c-48f5-871a-eca23c91404d", "name": "Elena \"Nell\" Cruz", "portrait_image_prompt": "1977 Chicana freelance radio journalist, late 20s, feathered dark hair, denim jacket over a mustard blouse, worn jeans, portable cassette recorder slung over one shoulder, dusty boots, intelligent wary eyes, tired but determined expression, subtle desert grime, cinematic horror visual novel portrait, semi-realistic painted style", "dialogue_examples": ["That's the third story I've heard about this motel tonight. Mind if I keep the recorder running?", "A vacancy sign with no power line is not normal. I'm not pretending it is.", "If someone's calling for help in there, dead or alive, I'm not driving away.", "Static doesn't say my name. Something here wants to be heard."]}}, "non_player_characters": [{"character_data": {"uuid": "788d6062-b0cb-4381-9e58-91ee047ab5e8", "name": "Lena Salazar", "portrait_image_prompt": "1977 New Mexico roadside waitress and former motel maid, early 40s, dark braided hair pinned back, lined face, turquoise earrings, faded floral blouse under a brown cardigan, cigarette burn on apron, worried eyes, carries a flashlight and rosary, desert night lighting, semi-realistic visual novel portrait", "dialogue_examples": ["The Starlight was wrong before it went empty. Empty just made it honest.", "If you hear the front desk bell after midnight, don't answer it and don't say your name.", "I scrubbed blood out of those sheets with bleach and prayer, and neither one worked.", "Folks around here survive by knowing when the desert wants something back."]}}, {"character_data": {"uuid": "5731d8c1-af20-470f-a3e3-39e7c03f22c7", "name": "Deputy Tom Baca", "portrait_image_prompt": "1977 rural New Mexico county deputy, late 30s, sun-weathered Hispanic man, tan sheriff uniform with brass badge, dark mustache, tired eyes, cowboy hat tucked under one arm, heavy flashlight, dust-covered patrol car headlights behind him, stoic but haunted expression, semi-realistic visual novel portrait", "dialogue_examples": ["Officially, there's no motel out there anymore. Unofficially, I tell people to keep driving.", "Every few years somebody swears that sign was lit. Every few years I write a report no one believes.", "I'm not paid enough to chase ghosts, but I am paid to keep you alive.", "My father answered a call at the Starlight in '61. He never came home."]}}, {"character_data": {"uuid": "052f9bd7-64e0-4e97-9755-3814ee077ad3", "name": "Theodore Bell", "portrait_image_prompt": "ghostly 1950s roadside motel manager lingering in 1977, gaunt middle-aged man in a cream shirt, thin tie, and dusty vest, slicked dark hair, polite smile hiding menace, pallid skin with faint corpse-like undertones, one hand near an old brass desk bell, flickering neon reflected in his eyes, elegant sinister visual novel portrait, semi-realistic painted style", "dialogue_examples": ["We always keep a room ready for stranded travelers.", "Out here, miss, the night is long. Hospitality is a mercy.", "The desert forgets people every day. I simply give them a place to stay.", "You checked in the moment you listened."]}}, {"character_data": {"uuid": "e426ab10-b052-42b0-884f-190183acfe1c", "name": "June Harrow", "portrait_image_prompt": "ghost of a 1960s teenage hitchhiker, about 16, pale freckled face, short sun-bleached hair, worn striped tee under a denim jacket, one strap of a vanished suitcase bag slipping from her shoulder, translucent edges, frightened but stubborn eyes, motel room lamplight and static distortion, haunting semi-realistic visual novel portrait", "dialogue_examples": ["He took my suitcase first. Said it would be safer in the office.", "Don't let him make you polite. That's how he gets inside your head.", "I kept waiting for morning. Morning never came in that room.", "If you tell the truth out loud, he can't tuck it back under the bed."]}}], "locations": [{"location_data": {"uuid": "2d50a3d7-ed01-4de2-80bc-154aa13b141b", "name": "Desert Highway Mile 117", "location_image_prompt": "lonely two-lane highway in rural New Mexico desert at night, 1977 setting, broken-down yellow Volkswagen Beetle on gravel shoulder, telephone poles stretching into darkness, distant mesas, cold moonlight, blowing dust, star-filled sky, ominous empty horizon, cinematic Southwestern horror background"}}, {"location_data": {"uuid": "1e174d03-6cbc-4ff9-ab05-2e89aed5a908", "name": "Starlight Motel Courtyard", "location_image_prompt": "abandoned U-shaped roadside motel in the New Mexico desert, 1977 Americana horror, cracked stucco walls, flickering red VACANCY sign, neon star emblem missing pieces, drained swimming pool, bent chain-link fence, tumbleweeds, parked rusted cars half-buried in sand, eerie midnight lighting, cinematic visual novel background"}}, {"location_data": {"uuid": "4fb2133a-6de9-4258-8d3a-f3afbc5b6e1b", "name": "Room 7", "location_image_prompt": "haunted 1970s motel room, faded floral wallpaper, sagging bedspread, rotary phone, buzzing bedside lamp, stained curtains, warped mirror, battered suitcase under the bed, portable cassette recorder on dresser, deep shadows in the bathroom doorway, oppressive paranormal atmosphere, semi-realistic horror background"}}, {"location_data": {"uuid": "71a4bb05-378f-470c-a8c6-a38a98bbfa57", "name": "Manager's Office and Boiler Room", "location_image_prompt": "front office of an abandoned roadside motel leading into a hidden boiler room, old brass bell on counter, wall of room keys, guest ledgers, rotary switchboard, dusty postcards, back door opening to rusted pipes and a furnace glow, stacks of stolen suitcases and personal effects, claustrophobic desert gothic horror background"}}], "intro_scene": {"scene_data": {"uuid": "21f651df-3233-422f-9c2c-40518f99a330", "scene_name": "intro", "location_uuid": "2d50a3d7-ed01-4de2-80bc-154aa13b141b", "non_player_character_uuids": ["5731d8c1-af20-470f-a3e3-39e7c03f22c7", "e426ab10-b052-42b0-884f-190183acfe1c"], "narrtive_summary": "On a deserted stretch of highway, Elena's car dies after her CB radio picks up a frightened girl's voice repeating, 'Room Seven.' Deputy Tom Baca arrives, recognizes the direction Elena describes, and reluctantly tells her the nearest shelter is the long-abandoned Starlight Motel while a dust storm closes the road. He warns her not to stay until dawn if she can help it. The intro establishes Elena's skeptical but compassionate nature, the isolated 1977 desert setting, and the first impossible sign that someone from the motel is still calling out."}}, "act_one": [{"scene_data": {"uuid": "06d1beec-2373-41b8-90a1-a96b1275a063", "scene_name": "act1_scene1", "location_uuid": "1e174d03-6cbc-4ff9-ab05-2e89aed5a908", "non_player_character_uuids": ["788d6062-b0cb-4381-9e58-91ee047ab5e8", "052f9bd7-64e0-4e97-9755-3814ee077ad3"], "narrtive_summary": "Elena reaches the Starlight Motel courtyard and finds the building somehow lit from within despite years of abandonment. Lena Salazar, who once worked there, appears with a flashlight and urgently tries to convince Elena to leave before the office bell rings. Before Elena can decide, Theodore Bell steps from the office as if the motel were still open for business and welcomes her with unnerving courtesy. The scene introduces the motel's false normalcy, Lena's fear, and Bell's predatory charisma."}}, {"scene_data": {"uuid": "c8fd2c0b-5486-4f34-870f-530e241615cd", "scene_name": "act1_scene2", "location_uuid": "4fb2133a-6de9-4258-8d3a-f3afbc5b6e1b", "non_player_character_uuids": ["052f9bd7-64e0-4e97-9755-3814ee077ad3", "e426ab10-b052-42b0-884f-190183acfe1c"], "narrtive_summary": "Inside Room 7, Elena records strange sounds on her cassette deck and discovers that the mirror reflects a teenage girl standing behind her. June Harrow slowly reveals herself as one of Bell's victims, while Bell keeps interrupting with polite offers of towels, coffee, and a 'quiet night's rest.' Elena learns that acknowledging Bell's hospitality seems to strengthen his hold, and that June has been trying to get someone to hear her testimony for years."}}], "act_two": [{"scene_data": {"uuid": "ad2a1f59-9247-4dce-8ce1-b277db0abea7", "scene_name": "act2_scene1", "location_uuid": "71a4bb05-378f-470c-a8c6-a38a98bbfa57", "non_player_character_uuids": ["5731d8c1-af20-470f-a3e3-39e7c03f22c7", "052f9bd7-64e0-4e97-9755-3814ee077ad3"], "narrtive_summary": "Deputy Baca returns to the motel to pull Elena out before sunrise, but the office reveals old ledgers filled with names of missing travelers and erased police notations. As Tom admits his own family history with the Starlight, Bell drops the mask of harmless host and traps them by cutting off the exits through the motel's impossible shifting layout. The scene turns the haunting into a concrete mystery with evidence, guilt, and the realization that Bell feeds on people accepting his version of events."}}, {"scene_data": {"uuid": "70b405fd-5e1a-42da-93e2-6ee8a1bc37e4", "scene_name": "act2_scene2", "location_uuid": "1e174d03-6cbc-4ff9-ab05-2e89aed5a908", "non_player_character_uuids": ["788d6062-b0cb-4381-9e58-91ee047ab5e8", "e426ab10-b052-42b0-884f-190183acfe1c"], "narrtive_summary": "Back in the courtyard, Lena helps Elena piece together the motel's history: Bell murdered vulnerable travelers, buried evidence in the furnace room, and turned the Starlight into a spiritual trap when he died in a fire he set himself. June manifests more clearly and explains that Bell's power depends on secrecy, false hospitality, and the silence of the dead. Elena decides the only way out is not escape but exposure: she must recover the truth and broadcast it before dawn."}}], "act_three": [{"scene_data": {"uuid": "17bd1f81-622f-4acf-a48e-87eb237e9422", "scene_name": "act3_scene1", "location_uuid": "71a4bb05-378f-470c-a8c6-a38a98bbfa57", "non_player_character_uuids": ["5731d8c1-af20-470f-a3e3-39e7c03f22c7", "052f9bd7-64e0-4e97-9755-3814ee077ad3", "e426ab10-b052-42b0-884f-190183acfe1c"], "narrtive_summary": "Elena, guided by June and backed by Tom, descends into the boiler room and finds decades of stolen suitcases, identification cards, and taped-over confession fragments Bell kept as trophies. Bell tries to break Elena by offering her a neat, comforting lie in place of the horror, forcing the player to reject his invitations and insist on naming the dead. Tom physically keeps the collapsing room open long enough for Elena to seize the guest ledger and June's hidden tape, giving them the proof needed to undo Bell."}}, {"scene_data": {"uuid": "91c0d24b-5ad6-4fc9-ad3a-bf018368ed0c", "scene_name": "act3_scene2", "location_uuid": "4fb2133a-6de9-4258-8d3a-f3afbc5b6e1b", "non_player_character_uuids": ["788d6062-b0cb-4381-9e58-91ee047ab5e8", "052f9bd7-64e0-4e97-9755-3814ee077ad3", "e426ab10-b052-42b0-884f-190183acfe1c"], "narrtive_summary": "In Room 7, the heart of the haunting, Elena uses her recorder to play June's final testimony aloud while Lena cuts power to the sign and Bell pounds at the door, trying to force his way back into the script of 'good service.' Speaking the victims' names and Bell's crimes strips away the motel's illusion; the room reverts from tidy false comfort to rotted ruin, and the trapped voices begin to leave. Bell makes one last attempt to persuade Elena to stay, but June helps Elena finish the broadcast and the Starlight starts to tear itself apart."}}], "outro_scene": {"scene_data": {"uuid": "35b99c7d-1fc5-4adb-8236-ff20865c19c1", "scene_name": "outro", "location_uuid": "2d50a3d7-ed01-4de2-80bc-154aa13b141b", "non_player_character_uuids": ["788d6062-b0cb-4381-9e58-91ee047ab5e8", "5731d8c1-af20-470f-a3e3-39e7c03f22c7"], "narrtive_summary": "At dawn on the highway, Elena, Lena, and Tom watch the desert reclaim the Starlight as its neon finally dies and the building settles into silent ruin. Elena records a final sign-off for her radio segment, now carrying real names instead of rumor, while Tom prepares to reopen the old missing-person cases and Lena faces the possibility of finally letting the dead rest. The denouement leaves a final chill when June's voice is heard one last time on the tape, no longer pleading, but quietly thanking Elena before the recorder clicks to silence."}}}"""

